properties.Title: Snow Squall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Snow squalls this morning. Snow squalls have developed over Lake Huron. The most intense snow squall is currently moving inland over Bayfield but is forecast to shift southward through the morning towards Exeter. Snowfall accumulations up to 15 cm will be possible today with these snow squalls. Heavy bursts of snow and significantly reduced visibilities at times can be expected through this morning. Motorists are advised to exercise caution and be prepared for quickly changing driving conditions. ### Snow squalls cause weather conditions to vary considerably; changes from clear skies to heavy snow within just a few kilometres are common. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.

properties.Title: Winter Storm Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A stationary Pacific frontal system will continue to give freezing rain mixed with snow to the Sea to Sky Highway north of Squamish. The freezing rain should be confined to north of Brandywine by this afternoon and then just in Whistler by late afternoon. ### Surfaces such as highways, roads, walkways and parking lots will become icy, slippery and hazardous. Poor weather conditions may contribute to transportation delays. Weather in the mountains can change suddenly resulting in hazardous driving conditions. Winter storm warnings are issued when multiple types of severe winter weather are expected to occur together. Road conditions are available at www.drivebc.ca. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm.

properties.Summary:
Description: Significant snowfall today Total snowfall: 10 to 20 cm, with up to 30 over parts of Victoria County. Maximum wind gusts: 50-70 km/h. Locations: central, northern, and eastern Nova Scotia Time span: today and this evening Remarks: Snow will continue throughout the afternoon for a majority of mainland Nova Scotia. Snowfall warnings are issued when significant snowfall is expected. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. properties.Title: Winter Storm Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Hazardous winter conditions are expected. A Pacific frontal system will remain stationary over the north coast. Consequently, heavy snow will continue through today, tonight and early Monday. Total snowfall accumulations of up to 50 cm are expected. In addition, there's the risk of freezing beginning tonight as warmer air moves in aloft. The snow will finally end near midday Monday as the front moves to the east. ### Visibility may be suddenly reduced at times in heavy snow. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm.

properties.Title: Rainfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Rain, at times heavy, is expected. A Pacific frontal system is giving heavy rain to West and North Vancouver Island. 50 to 70 mm of rain is forecast by Sunday evening for most communities of West Vancouver Island and North Vancouver Island including Tofino and Port Hardy. However higher rainfall amounts are forecast near Zeballos and near Port Alice where 100 mm of rain is anticipated by Sunday evening. ### Localized flooding in low-lying areas is possible. properties.Title: Snow Squall Watch In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Snow squalls are expected to develop. Under the snow squall bands, visibilities will be significantly reduced due to the heavy snow combined with blowing snow, and snow will quickly accumulate. Snow squalls from Southern Lake Huron may move into Western Lambton County later this afternoon and persist through tonight. Snowfall amounts in the strongest snow squalls may reach 15 cm tonight. Dangerous winter driving conditions are possible tonight in many areas including Highway 402. Snow squalls will weaken to a few flurries Monday morning. ### Snow squalls cause weather conditions to vary considerably; changes from clear skies to heavy snow within just a few kilometres are common. Visibility may be significantly and suddenly reduced to near zero. Road closures are possible. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.

properties.Title: Extreme Cold Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A period of very cold wind chills is expected. Light northwesterly winds combined with temperatures in the minus thirties will produce windchill values of -40 or lower through the early morning hours. Windchill values will moderate during the day on Sunday, however they may return to warning levels over southeastern Saskatchewan Sunday night into Monday morning. ### Watch for cold related symptoms: shortness of breath, chest pain, muscle pain and weakness, numbness and colour change in fingers and toes. properties.Title: Snow Squall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Snow squalls today. A strong snow squall off of Southern Lake Huron extends from near Grand Bend across London to the Thamesford and Ingersoll areas. Snowfall amounts of 10 to 15 cm in a few hours are possible with this snow squall. In addition, sudden near zero visibility from blowing snow and bursts of heavy snow are expected as the snow squall moves in. The snow squall will move south of the area this afternoon. However new snow squalls are expected to develop off of Southern Lake Huron later this afternoon when the winds shift to a more northerly direction. These will affect Eastern Lambton County and Middlesex County mainly west of the City of London. ### Snow squalls cause weather conditions to vary considerably; changes from clear skies to heavy snow within just a few kilometres are common. Visibility will be suddenly reduced to near zero at times in heavy snow and blowing snow. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.
